Preparation¶

Eric Houtman, Rick Lattin, Kellen Long

We plan to use accuracy as the metric for our model performance. This metric is appropriate for our data due to the fact that the application of our models is for the classification of sentiment as purely positive or negative. The nature of the classification of this few categories makes it so that the percentage of the testing data that is guessed correctly by the classifier is what is most valuable when judging the model, as the model has no continuous range of answers to try and estimate from. Hence we use accuracy. Furthermore, the fact that the classes are polar oppposites of each other makes the use of accuracy as our metric an even more appropriate choice.

We first remove any special characters from the text and split the text into individual words. This is done to improve the effectiveness and ease of the tokenization process. We also prepare a copy of the data to be used with the Glove pre-trained embedding later in the program.

In [201]:
#remove any nun-ascii characters
df['text'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: x.encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('ascii'))

#make all text lowercase
df['text'] = df['text'].str.lower()

#remove any non-alphanumeric characters
df['text'] = df['text'].str.replace('[^0-9a-zA-Z]+', ' ')

#separate the text into words

We decided to implement a word-based method of tokenization in which we collect data regarding individual word frequency using the keras preprocessing tokenizer. This method lends itself very well to our classification task, as we are only working with text from the English language, a language that puts a lot of emphasis on individual words as opposed to strings of charcters or word-parts. Furthermore, although there are a few instances of slang or made-up words to convey meaning within the context of the reviews we are analyzing, the vast majority of the reviews rely exclusivley on the same collection of recognized English words, making the use of word based tokenization even more effective.

For this dataset, we used ShuffleSplit to partition the data. We felt this was a sufficient strategy due to the fact that the class ratioes of the testing data (positive, negative) are already at about an even split, so stratifying it is not necessary and we are able to save some computational power by implimenting shuffle split over a method that would have statified the data. We maintain a 75/25 split in the data.

In [203]:

We decided on a length of 500 characters for the size of the sequence that is to be reviewed as we believed that, for the context of our dataset of IMDB movie reviews, 500 charcters would be enough space to determine sentiment without having a substantial amount of unnecessary space to be padded.

In [204]:
# truncate and pad input sequences to be the same length
max_review_length = 500
X_train = sequence.pad_sequences(X_train, maxlen=max_review_length)
X_test = sequence.pad_sequences(X_test, maxlen=max_review_length)

First Model - Simple Recurrent Neural Network¶

We chose standard hyperparameters for our first model as recommeneded by models given by Professor Larson. We believed they would give us a manageable run time while preventing overfitting and providing a relatively high accuracy.

Modified First Model - Different hyperparameters¶

The first hyperparameter we decided to change for this model was the variable EMBED_SIZE which determines the size of the embedding layer. The size of the embedding layer is doubled from 50 to 100, which increases the dimensionality of the vector representation of each word. Although this increases the amount of time needed for the training of the model, it allows the model to capture more detailed information about the text, which should improve the accuracy of the model. We chose to alter this parameter to analyze whether the change in accuracy would be worth the increase in the run time.

We also decided to change the activation function of the first dense layer of the model. We changed the activation function from the 'sigmoid' activation function to the 'relu' activation function. Although the 'sigmoid' function is primarily used with binary classifcation tasks - which is why we implemented it first - it occasionally has problems with the vanishing gradients. The 'relu' function struggles less with this and so we implemented this activation function here in order to determine whether deviating from the industry standard of activation functions for binary classification would improve the performance of our specific model by dealing with the vanishing gradient problem.

modified_simple_RNN = Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)

Modified Second Model - Different hyperparameters¶

The only hyperparameter we decided to change for this model was the activation fucntion of the first dense layer of the LSTM model. We changed the activation function from the 'sigmoid' activation function to the 'relu' activation function. As we mentioned earlier, although the 'sigmoid' function is primarily used with binary classifcation tasks - which is why we implemented it first - it occasionally has problems with the vanishing gradients. The 'relu' function struggles less with this and so we implemented this activation function here in order to determine whether deviating from the industry standard of activation functions for binary classification would improve the performance of our specific model by dealing with the vanishing gradient problem.

In [240]:
%%time
EMBED_SIZE = 100
# the embed size should match the file you load glove from
embeddings_index = {}
f = open('glove/glove.6B.100d.txt', encoding='utf8')
print('Loading GloVe from:', f.name,'...this may take a while...')
for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32') # shape (300,)
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()
print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

found_words = 0
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be ALL-ZEROS
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        found_words = found_words+1

print("Embedding Shape:",embedding_matrix.shape, "\n",
      "Total words found:",found_words, "\n",
      "Percentage:",100*found_words/embedding_matrix.shape[0])

Grad Section - Converting back to Convolutional Neural Network¶

We chose standard hyperparameters for our first LSTM model as recommeneded by models given by Professor Larson. We believed they would give us a manageable run time while preventing overfitting, preventing vanishing gradients and providing a relatively high accuracy.

In [247]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten, Dense
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Input, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding

EMBED_SIZE = 100 
sequence_input = Input(shape=(MAX_ART_LEN,), dtype='int32')
# starting size: 1000
embedded_sequences = embedding_layer(sequence_input) # from previous embedding
x = Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(embedded_sequences)

# after conv, size becomes: 1000-4=996
x = Dropout(0.05)(x)
x = MaxPooling1D(5)(x)# after max pool, 996/5 = 199
x = Dropout(0.15)(x)
x = Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

# new size is 195
x = MaxPooling1D(5)(x) # after max pool, size is 195/5 = 39
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

# after convolution, size becomes 35 elements long
x = MaxPooling1D(35)(x) # this is the size to globally flatten 
# flattened vector max pools across each of the 35 elements
# so vectors is now 128 dimensions (same as num output filters)
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dropout(0.25)(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu',
          kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

preds = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='softmax',
              kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform')(x)

model = Model(sequence_input, preds)
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['acc'])

print(model.summary())
histories = []
tmp = model.fit(X_train, y_train_ohe, validation_data=(X_test, y_test_ohe),
          epochs=2, batch_size=128)
histories.append(tmp)

from sklearn import metrics as mt
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

# combine all the history from training together
combined = dict()
for key in ['acc','val_acc','loss','val_loss']:
    combined[key] = np.hstack([x.history[key] for x in histories])
    
# summarize history for accuracy
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
plt.subplot(121)
plt.plot(combined['acc'])
plt.plot(combined['val_acc'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')

# summarize history for loss
plt.subplot(122)
plt.plot(combined['loss'])
plt.plot(combined['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()
